T1  - The Occurrence of Structural Hysteresis In Declining Organizations , 
AU  - Ford, Jeffrey D.
Y1  - 1980/10/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1980.4288964
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1980.4288964
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 589
EP  - 598
VL  - 5
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Structural hysteresis provides a conceptual framework in which to consider relationships between organization size and structure during periods of decline. The use of this framework, as an extension of current theory, indicates that relationships between size and structure in declining organizations do not parallel those found in growing organizations. Participation problems, commitment, and coalition politics may explain the occurrence of structural hysteresis. Implications for theory and research are discussed.
AB  - Structural hysteresis provides a conceptual framework in which to consider relationships between organization size and structure during periods of decline. The use of this framework, as an extension of current theory, indicates that relationships between size and structure in declining organizations do not parallel those found in growing organizations. Participation problems, commitment, and coalition politics may explain the occurrence of structural hysteresis. Implications for theory and research are discussed.
